description: Borrowed from Latin serrātus, past participle of serrō.

adjectives.description: serrate (comparative more serrate, superlative most serrate)

entries.meaning: Having tooth-like projections on one side, as in a saw.
examples: Many click beetles have serrate antennae.

entries.meaning: (botany) Of leaves: having tooth-like projections pointed away from the petiole.

verbs.description: serrate (third-person singular simple present serrates, present participle serrating, simple past and past participle serrated)

entries.meaning: To cut or divide in a jagged way.
